ornia. She finds that these "alternative" prisons, contrary to their aims, often end up disempowering women, transforming their social vulnerabilities into personal pathologies, and pushing them into a state of disentitlement. Uncovering the complex gendered underpinning of methods of control and intervention used in the criminal justice system today, Offending Women links that system to broader discussions on contemporary government and state power, asks why these strategies have arisen at this particular moment in time, and considers what forms of citizenship they have given rise to.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCorrectional institutionszCaliforniavCase studies. 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitationzCaliforniavCase studies. 0aFemale offenderszCaliforniavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aalternative community based prisons.  aalternative prisons for women.  acontemporary government and state power.  acontrol and intervention.  adisempowering women.  aeye opening.  aincarcerated women.  ainstitutions in california.  amothers housed together with children.  aobservations of daily life.  apower over womens minds and bodies.  ashocking.  asocial vulnerabilities into personal pathologies.  astate of disentitlement.  astudy of incarcerated women.  avivid.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026190740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094591340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945913/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY